"{\"uid\": \"limerickleader.ie-news-national-news-1562645-gardai-to-be-deployed-in-paris-for-olympics-amid-terrorism-fears.html\", \"text\": \"Limerick Live  https://www.limerickleader.ie/section/1195/advertise-with-us  Search  06 Dec 2025  Bringing you live local breaking news, sport, politics, weather & more in Limerick and County Limerick  All the latest breaking local news from Limerick and County Limerick  Keep up to date with the latest sports news  Ryder Cup  Read all the latest Irish news and updates from around Ireland  Find whats happening in and around Limerick and County Limerick  Life Magazines  Enjoy our award winning photos and picture galleries taken in Limerick and County Limerick  Catch up on all the latest business news in Limerick and County Limerick  Read about the latest properties available in Limerick and County Limerick  Enjoy our latest and up to date motoring review and news in Limerick and County Limerick  Limerick and County Limerick Met Eireann Weather Forecast  Recent death notices and obituaries from Limerick and County Limerick  Please allow ads as they help fund our trusted local news content.  Kindly addusto your ad blocker whitelist.  If you want further access to Ireland's best local journalism, consider contributing and/or subscribing to our free daily Newsletter .  Support our mission and join our community now.  To continue reading this article, you can subscribe for as little as \\u20ac0.50 per week which will also give you access to all of our premium content and archived articles!  Alternatively, you can pay \\u20ac0.50 per article, capped at \\u20ac1 per day.  Thank you for supporting Ireland's best local journalism!  PICTURE: Sportsfile  Reporter:  Reporter  24 Jul 2024 3:53 PM  The 2024 Olympics are just around the corner and the French capital is undergoing an 'elaborate' and 'unprecedented' security operation to deal with the crowds.  About 25,000 Irish fans expected to travel to the city, and as a result, Irish garda\\u00ed will be among the forces deployed to ensure the safety of both participants and spectators.  The security measures in Paris are extensive, including an anti-terrorism border along the River Seine, extending 6 kilometers on both sides. The scene is one of 'high' security: about six roads converging at a major junction will see three blocked off by metal barriers. Meanwhile, dozens of police officers are to be standing at roadblocks and checking QR codes to verify locals' addresses and conducting thorough checks of their bags before admission.  The opening ceremony, which will take place along the Seine rather than inside a stadium, will see a no-fly zone extending 150 kilometers above the ceremony site while snipers will be deployed on rooftops to maintain surveillance and ensure safety. RT\\u00c9's Kate Varley, reporting from Paris, said: \\\"It's safe to say that rarely in peacetime has the French capital experienced such high levels of security.\\\"  Mark Hecker, a security analyst with the French Institute of International Relations, highlighted the various threats the authorities are preparing for. \\\"This is a huge event attracting millions of people. The main threat for the French authorities is terrorism, specifically the jihadist threat. However, there are also concerns about far-right activists and non-violent disruptors. Additionally, the cyber threat is significant, but the authorities are well-prepared to counter it.\\\"  To maximize protection and minimize risks, French authorities have mobilised 45,000 police officers andgendarmes, over 10,000 soldiers, and 20,000 private security officers. In response to a request from French authorities, 42 Garda\\u00ed from Ireland will assist in policing Paris from July 25 to August 12, with a further 12 Garda\\u00ed for the Paralympics from August 27 to September 9. An additional two Garda\\u00ed will assist in tourist areas.  Inspector Neil Casserly, International Liaison with An Garda S\\u00edoch\\u00e1na, stated: \\\"Our Garda\\u00ed will be partaking in joint patrols with French police and will assist Irish nationals, as well as other English-speaking attendees. Their missions include assuring public security, welcoming visitors, and facilitating engagement, as well as securing transport in train and metro stations around central Paris, particularly in the 5th, 6th, 9th, 11th, and 15th arrondissements.\\\"  This deployment follows recent successful cooperation during the World Cup held in Bordeaux. The Irish garda\\u00ed's presence in Paris aims to enhance the overall safety and experience of the visiting Irish fans, contributing to a secure and enjoyable Olympic Games.  Related topics:  in1  4  To continue reading this article,please subscribe and support local journalism!  Subscribing will allow you access to all of our premium content and archived articles.  To continue reading this article for FREE,please kindly register and/or log in.  Registration is absolutely 100% FREE and will help us personalise your experience on our sites.  You can also sign up to our carefully curated newsletter(s) to keep up to date with your latest local news!  Most Popular  Farmer Eamonn Sheehan died following a fall on his farm on Tuesday  Local News  The former Debenhams building in Limerick city centre has been out of use since Easter 2020 when the British retailer collapsed | PICTURE: Adrian Butler  Local News  Crime and Courts  Eleven letters were sent to the garda sergeant over 18 months  Crime and Courts  Kilmallock Tourism Community Employment Scheme\\u00a0is the only CE scheme in Ireland with an official Service Level Agreement with a local authorit  Local News  Sponsored Content  Sponsored Content  Sponsored Content  Sponsored  Sponsored Content  With dark evenings closing in, it's the perfect time to curl up with a hot chocolate, a cosy blanket, and the November/December edition of Limerick Life  Sponsored Content  Multimedia  CMAT, Roy Keane, Shane Lowry and Kingfishr 